<TEI xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" xmlns:frus="http://history.state.gov/frus/ns/1.0"><text><body><div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1946-06-17T19:00:00-05:00" frus:doc-dateTime-min="1946-06-17T19:00:00-05:00" n="213" subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d213">
                        <note rend="inline" type="source">740.00119 Control (Japan)/6–1846:
                            Telegram</note>
                        <head><hi rend="italic">The Counselor of Embassy in China</hi> (<persName type="from"><hi rend="italic">Smyth</hi></persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of
                                State</gloss></hi></head>
                        <opener>
                            <seg rendition="#left"><hi rend="smallcaps">Confidential</hi></seg>
                            <dateline rendition="#right"><placeName><hi rend="smallcaps">Nanking</hi></placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1946-06-18T09:00:00+09:00">June 18, 1946—9
                                a.m.</date><lb/>[Received June 18—7:20 a.m.]</dateline>
                        </opener>
                        <p>1001. ReEmbtel 745, May 3.<note n="24" xml:id="d213fn1">Not printed, but
                                see footnote 9, <ref target="#pg_238">p. 238</ref>.</note> 67th
                            Division (formerly honored Second Division of 53rd Army) has been
                            designated basic unit of Chinese occupation force to be sent to Japan.
                            Total strength this force, supplemented by necessary service personnel,
                            is 12,367 officers and men. Units this force concentrated Shanghai,
                            Kowloon and Haiphong and will depart for Japan upon receipt notice from
                                <gloss target="#t_SCAP1">SCAP</gloss> and arrival of ships for
                                transportation.<note n="25" xml:id="d213fn2">An exchange of notes
                                confirming arrangements for the Chinese occupation force in Japan
                                was finally completed; see the note of October 4 to the Chinese
                                Ambassador, <ref target="#pg_329">p. 329</ref>.</note></p>
                        <closer><signed><hi rend="smallcaps">Smyth</hi></signed></closer>
                    </div>
                    </body></text></TEI>